{
  "The deltoid muscle is responsible for:": "",
  "Knee extension and straightening of the lower leg": "",
  "Shoulder abduction (raising the arm to the side)": "",
  "Elbow flexion and curling of the forearm upward": "",
  "Trunk flexion and forward bending of the torso": "",
  "The deltoid is a thick, triangular muscle capping the shoulder that is the primary abductor of the arm, lifting it laterally away from the body, though its anterior and posterior fibers also assist with flexion and extension.": "",
  "The biceps brachii primarily performs:": "",
  "Knee extension": "",
  "Elbow extension and pronation": "",
  "Elbow flexion and forearm supination": "",
  "Hip flexion": "",
  "The biceps brachii, a two-headed muscle on the anterior arm, is a powerful elbow flexor and the strongest supinator of the forearm, which is why we turn our palm up when tightening a screw.": "",
  "The triceps brachii is the primary muscle for:": "",
  "Wrist flexion": "",
  "Elbow flexion": "",
  "Elbow extension": "",
  "Shoulder abduction": "",
  "The triceps brachii is a three-headed muscle on the posterior arm that serves as the primary extensor of the elbow joint, working as the antagonist to the biceps brachii.": "",
  "The quadriceps group consists of how many muscles?": "",
  "Three (rectus femoris, vastus lateralis, and vastus medialis)": "",
  "Five (the four vastus muscles plus the sartorius as a fifth member)": "",
  "Two (the rectus femoris and a single combined vastus muscle)": "",
  "Four (rectus femoris, vastus lateralis, vastus medialis, vastus intermedius)": "",
  "The quadriceps femoris group ('quad' meaning four) includes the rectus femoris, vastus lateralis, vastus medialis, and vastus intermedius, all of which converge on the patellar tendon and work together to extend the knee.": "",
  "The primary action of the quadriceps group is:": "",
  "Hip extension": "",
  "Knee flexion": "",
  "Ankle dorsiflexion": "",
  "The quadriceps group is the powerful extensor of the knee, essential for standing up from a seated position, climbing stairs, kicking, and stabilizing the knee during walking and running.": "",
  "The hamstring muscles include:": "",
  "Gluteus maximus, medius, and minimus": "",
  "Rectus femoris, vastus lateralis, vastus medialis": "",
  "Gastrocnemius and soleus": "",
  "Biceps femoris, semimembranosus, and semitendinosus": "",
  "The hamstring group comprises three muscles on the posterior thigh (biceps femoris, semimembranosus, and semitendinosus) that work together to flex the knee and extend the hip.": "",
  "The gluteus maximus primarily performs:": "",
  "Ankle plantar flexion": "",
  "The gluteus maximus is the largest and most superficial gluteal muscle and is the most powerful extensor of the hip, essential for activities like climbing stairs, rising from a squat, running, and jumping.": "",
  "The gastrocnemius muscle performs:": "",
  "Plantar flexion of the ankle (pointing toes down/calf raise)": "",
  "Dorsiflexion of the ankle (pulling toes upward toward the shin)": "",
  "Hip abduction (moving the thigh laterally away from midline)": "",
  "Knee extension (straightening the lower leg at the knee joint)": "",
  "The gastrocnemius is the large, superficial calf muscle that, along with the deeper soleus, performs plantar flexion at the ankle, which is critical for pushing off the ground during walking, running, and jumping.": "",
  "The rectus abdominis performs:": "",
  "Hip abduction": "",
  "Spinal extension and back arching": "",
  "Trunk (spinal) flexion, as in sit-ups and crunches": "",
  "Shoulder rotation": "",
  "The rectus abdominis is the long, flat 'six-pack' muscle running vertically along the anterior abdomen that is the primary flexor of the lumbar spine, drawing the ribcage toward the pelvis during sit-ups and crunches.": "",
  "The diaphragm is the primary muscle of:": "",
  "Breathing (inspiration)": "",
  "Blood circulation": "",
  "Posture maintenance": "",
  "Digestion": "",
  "The diaphragm is a dome-shaped skeletal muscle separating the thoracic and abdominal cavities that contracts and flattens during inspiration, increasing thoracic volume and drawing air into the lungs, accounting for about 75% of the air movement during quiet breathing.": "",
  "What is an agonist (prime mover)?": "",
  "The muscle primarily responsible for producing a specific movement": "",
  "A muscle that assists another muscle with the same action": "",
  "A muscle that opposes the desired movement": "",
  "A muscle that stabilizes a joint without producing movement": "",
  "An agonist (or prime mover) is the muscle that bears the primary responsibility for a particular movement, such as the biceps brachii being the agonist for elbow flexion or the quadriceps being the agonist for knee extension.": "",
  "What is an antagonist muscle?": "",
  "A muscle that has no function during movement": "",
  "A muscle that opposes or reverses the action of the agonist": "",
  "The main muscle producing a desired movement": "",
  "A muscle that helps the agonist perform its action": "",
  "An antagonist is a muscle that opposes the action of the agonist, providing controlled resistance and smooth movement; for example, the triceps brachii is the antagonist to the biceps brachii during elbow flexion, relaxing to allow flexion and contracting to produce extension.": "",
  "What is a synergist muscle?": "",
  "Another name for the antagonist": "",
  "A muscle that directly opposes the agonist": "",
  "A muscle that is completely inactive during a movement": "",
  "A muscle that assists the agonist by adding force to the same movement or reducing unnecessary movement": "",
  "A synergist is a muscle that assists the prime mover by contributing to the same movement, stabilizing joints to prevent unwanted motions, or neutralizing undesired actions of the agonist, such as the brachialis assisting the biceps during elbow flexion.": "",
  "What does 'origin' mean when describing a muscle's attachment?": "",
  "The middle portion (belly) of the muscle": "",
  "The attachment point on the bone that moves during contraction": "",
  "The attachment point on the more stationary (fixed) bone that serves as the anchor during contraction": "",
  "The point where the nerve enters the muscle": "",
  "The origin is the proximal or less movable attachment point of a muscle, typically on the more stable bone, which serves as the anchor from which the muscle pulls during contraction, such as the scapula being the origin of the biceps brachii.": "",
  "What does 'insertion' mean when describing a muscle's attachment?": "",
  "The attachment point on the bone that moves when the muscle contracts, typically the more distal attachment": "",
  "The point where the nerve inserts into the muscle fiber": "",
  "The connective tissue layer surrounding the muscle": "",
  "The center of the muscle belly": "",
  "The insertion is the distal or more movable attachment point of a muscle, on the bone that is pulled toward the origin during contraction, such as the radial tuberosity being the insertion of the biceps brachii.": "",
  "What is the latissimus dorsi?": "",
  "A small muscle of the neck that rotates the head": "",
  "A thigh muscle that extends the knee": "",
  "A muscle of the anterior chest that flexes and adducts the arm": "",
  "A broad, flat muscle of the posterior trunk that extends, adducts, and medially rotates the arm": "",
  "The latissimus dorsi ('lat') is the broadest muscle of the back, extending from the lower spine and iliac crest to the humerus, responsible for powerful arm extension, adduction, and medial rotation, as used in pull-ups, swimming, and rowing.": "",
  "What is the pectoralis major?": "",
  "An abdominal muscle that compresses the abdomen": "",
  "A large, fan-shaped muscle of the anterior chest that flexes, adducts, and medially rotates the arm at the shoulder": "",
  "A leg muscle that extends the knee": "",
  "A back muscle that extends the spine": "",
  "The pectoralis major is a large, fan-shaped muscle covering the upper anterior chest, originating from the clavicle, sternum, and ribs and inserting on the humerus; it is the primary muscle for chest press movements, push-ups, and bringing the arms across the body.": "",
  "What is the erector spinae?": "",
  "A single large muscle that flexes the trunk forward": "",
  "A group of muscles running along the vertebral column that extend and stabilize the spine for upright posture": "",
  "A rotator cuff muscle that stabilizes the shoulder": "",
  "A hip flexor muscle located in the anterior thigh": "",
  "The erector spinae is a group of three paired muscle columns (iliocostalis, longissimus, and spinalis) running along the length of the vertebral column that are the primary extensors of the spine, maintaining upright posture and controlling trunk flexion.": "",
  "What is the sternocleidomastoid (SCM)?": "",
  "An abdominal wall muscle that compresses the internal organs, assists in forced expiration, and helps stabilize the trunk during lifting": "",
  "A deep muscle of the lower back that extends and laterally flexes the vertebral column, running alongside the spinous processes from the sacrum upward": "",
  "A triangular muscle of the shoulder that abducts the arm, originating from the clavicle and scapular spine and inserting on the deltoid tuberosity": "",
  "A prominent neck muscle that flexes the neck and rotates the head, originating from the sternum and clavicle and inserting on the mastoid process": "",
  "The sternocleidomastoid is a large, strap-like neck muscle named for its attachments (sternum, clavicle, and mastoid process of the temporal bone) that, when contracting unilaterally, rotates the head to the opposite side, and bilaterally, flexes the neck.": "",
  "What does 'abduction' mean as a muscle action?": "",
  "Movement of a limb toward the midline of the body": "",
  "Bending a joint to decrease the angle between bones": "",
  "Rotation of a limb around its long axis": "",
  "Movement of a limb away from the midline of the body": "",
  "Abduction is the movement of a body part away from the midline of the body, such as raising the arm laterally (performed by the deltoid) or spreading the fingers apart, and is the opposite of adduction (movement toward the midline).": "",
  "A physical therapist is working with a patient who tore her ACL and has been in a knee brace for 6 weeks. The therapist notes significant wasting of the patient's quadriceps. Why did the quadriceps atrophy, and what exercises would the therapist prioritize during rehabilitation?": "",
  "The quadriceps converted to smooth muscle during immobilization": "",
  "The quadriceps atrophied from disuse during immobilization; the therapist would prioritize progressive knee extension exercises to rebuild the quadriceps since they are critical for knee stability": "",
  "The quadriceps did not actually atrophy; the apparent size decrease is just swelling reduction": "",
  "The quadriceps atrophied because the ACL tear directly damaged the muscle; the therapist would focus on hamstring curls only": "",
  "Immobilization after ACL injury causes rapid disuse atrophy of the quadriceps because the muscles are not being loaded; rehabilitation prioritizes progressive quadriceps strengthening (isometric to isotonic) because strong quadriceps are essential for dynamic knee stability and protecting the reconstructed ligament.": "",
  "A patient who had a stroke has difficulty raising her left arm above her head to brush her hair. The neurologist explains that the stroke damaged the motor cortex area controlling the left shoulder. Which muscle is primarily affected, preventing arm abduction?": "",
  "Rectus abdominis": "",
  "Gastrocnemius": "",
  "Biceps brachii": "",
  "Deltoid": "",
  "The deltoid is the primary abductor of the shoulder, and damage to the motor cortex area controlling it would prevent the patient from raising her arm laterally, making overhead activities like hair brushing, reaching shelves, and dressing extremely difficult.": "",
  "A personal trainer asks a client to perform a biceps curl. As the client lifts the dumbbell, the biceps brachii shortens. What role does the triceps brachii play during this movement, and what type of muscle relationship does this illustrate?": "",
  "The triceps is the agonist and contracts to help lift the weight": "",
  "The triceps is a synergist that adds force to the curl": "",
  "The triceps plays no role during the biceps curl": "",
  "The triceps is the antagonist and must relax (or eccentrically control) to allow smooth elbow flexion by the biceps": "",
  "During elbow flexion, the biceps is the agonist and the triceps is the antagonist; the triceps must relax and yield to allow the biceps to shorten the joint angle, illustrating the agonist-antagonist relationship where opposing muscles coordinate to produce smooth, controlled movement.": "",
  "An emergency medicine resident is evaluating a patient who was in a car accident and cannot extend his right knee against resistance. Imaging shows the patellar tendon is ruptured. Which muscle group has lost its ability to transmit force to the tibia?": "",
  "The quadriceps femoris group": "",
  "The gluteal muscles": "",
  "The gastrocnemius and soleus": "",
  "The hamstrings": "",
  "The patellar tendon transmits the combined force of all four quadriceps muscles from the patella to the tibial tuberosity; when ruptured, the quadriceps can still contract but cannot extend the knee because the force transmission pathway to the lower leg is severed.": "",
  "A yoga instructor notices that a student has difficulty maintaining an upright seated posture and tends to slouch forward. Which muscle group along the posterior trunk is likely weak and needs strengthening?": "",
  "Quadriceps": "",
  "Erector spinae": "",
  "The erector spinae muscles are the primary extensors and stabilizers of the vertebral column; weakness in these muscles leads to inability to maintain upright posture, resulting in excessive forward flexion (slouching) and potential back pain.": "",
  "A sprinter pulls up suddenly during a race, clutching the back of her thigh. The team physician diagnoses a hamstring strain. Based on hamstring anatomy, which specific movement likely caused the injury during sprinting?": "",
  "The rapid eccentric contraction of the hamstrings as they decelerate the extending knee during the swing phase of sprinting": "",
  "The forceful hip abduction during lateral movement placed excessive stress on the gluteal muscles and tensor fasciae latae": "",
  "Overloading of the quadriceps during explosive knee extension in the push-off phase exceeded the tendon's tensile strength": "",
  "Extreme ankle plantar flexion during the toe-off phase overstressed the gastrocnemius and soleus muscles of the posterior calf": "",
  "During sprinting, the hamstrings must eccentrically contract to decelerate the rapidly extending knee during the late swing phase; this puts enormous tensile stress on the muscle-tendon unit and is the most common mechanism of hamstring strains in sprinters.": "",
  "A respiratory therapist is treating a patient with a spinal cord injury at the C3-C5 level. The therapist explains that the patient cannot breathe independently because the phrenic nerve is damaged. Which muscle is paralyzed, and why is it so critical?": "",
  "The intercostal muscles, which are the only muscles of breathing": "",
  "The sternocleidomastoid, which is the only muscle needed for breathing": "",
  "The rectus abdominis, which controls all breathing movements": "",
  "The diaphragm, which is the primary muscle of inspiration and is innervated by the phrenic nerve (C3-C5)": "",
  "The diaphragm is the primary muscle of inspiration, responsible for about 75% of air movement during quiet breathing, and it is innervated by the phrenic nerve originating from C3-C5; damage to these spinal cord segments paralyzes the diaphragm and requires mechanical ventilation.": "",
  "A patient complains of a stiff neck after sleeping in an awkward position. The doctor diagnoses a strained sternocleidomastoid muscle. The patient notices she can only turn her head to the right comfortably. On which side is the SCM most likely strained?": "",
  "The right SCM, because it turns the head to the right": "",
  "The left SCM, because unilateral contraction of the left SCM rotates the head to the right (contralateral rotation)": "",
  "Both SCMs are equally strained": "",
  "Neither SCM is involved; the trapezius is responsible": "",
  "The sternocleidomastoid rotates the head to the opposite side when contracting unilaterally; if the left SCM is strained, turning the head to the right (which requires left SCM contraction) would be more comfortable since the strained muscle is already shortened, while turning left would painfully stretch it.": "",
  "A bodybuilder is performing a bench press. During the upward pressing phase, which major muscle group acts as the primary agonist, and what is the type of contraction?": "",
  "Biceps brachii performing an isometric contraction": "",
  "Pectoralis major performing a concentric contraction to push the weight upward": "",
  "Erector spinae performing a concentric contraction": "",
  "Latissimus dorsi performing an eccentric contraction": "",
  "During the pressing (upward) phase of the bench press, the pectoralis major is the primary agonist performing a concentric contraction, shortening to push the barbell upward through horizontal adduction and flexion of the shoulder, assisted by the anterior deltoid and triceps.": "",
  "A physical therapist is treating an elderly patient who had a hip replacement and now has difficulty climbing stairs and rising from a chair. Which major muscle must the therapist prioritize strengthening to restore these functional abilities?": "",
  "Gluteus maximus": "",
  "The gluteus maximus is the most powerful hip extensor and is the primary muscle used for climbing stairs, rising from a seated position, and propelling the body forward during walking; strengthening this muscle is critical for restoring functional independence after hip replacement surgery.": ""
}